  "prompt": "When and how did WWI start and end?",
  "response": "World War I (WWI) began on July 28, 1914, and ended on November 11, 1918. The war started following a complex web of alliances and tensions among European nations, but its immediate catalyst was the assassination of Archduke Franz Ferdinand of Austria-Hungary on June 28, 1914, in Sarajevo. This event triggered a series of diplomatic crises, leading to the mobilization of forces and declarations of war.\n\nHere\u2019s a brief timeline of significant events leading up to and during the war:\n\n- **July 23, 1914**: Austria-Hungary issued an ultimatum to Serbia, which included demands that were difficult for Serbia to accept fully. \n- **July 25, 1914**: Serbia responded to the ultimatum, agreeing to most but not all of the demands.\n- **July 28, 1914**: Austria-Hungary declared war on Serbia.\n- **July 30, 1914**: Russia began to mobilize its army in defense of Serbia.\n- **August 1, 1914**: Germany declared war on Russia.\n- **August 3, 1914**: Germany declared war on France, and shortly after invaded Belgium, bringing Britain into the war on August 4, 1914, due to its obligation to protect Belgian neutrality.\n\nThe war involved many of the world\u2019s great powers and was characterized by trench warfare, significant loss of life, and widespread destruction. The main combatants were divided into two main alliances: the Allies (which included countries like France, the United Kingdom, Russia, and later the United States) and the Central Powers (primarily Germany, Austria-Hungary, the Ottoman Empire, and Bulgaria).\n\nWWI effectively ended with the signing of the Armistice of Compi\u00e8gne on November 11, 1918, at 11:00 a.m. Following the armistice, a series of peace treaties were negotiated and signed, with the most notable being the Treaty of Versailles, signed on June 28, 1919. This treaty placed heavy reparations and territorial losses on Germany, contributing to economic hardship and political instability in the country, which later played a role in the rise of WWII.",
